; ============================================================
; SECTION 1 — What functional programming does well for logic + reasoning
; ============================================================

(section :n 1 :title "What functional programming does well for logic and reasoning"

  :prose "
Scheme sits at a peculiar spot in the map of programming languages: it
was designed at MIT in 1975 by Sussman and Steele partly as a testbed
for the actor model, partly as a small Lisp that could hold its own
in an undergraduate curriculum, and — as it turned out — one of the
best languages we have for writing programs that reason about programs.
The book that carried that mission furthest is Abelson and Sussman's
_Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs_ (MIT Press, 1985;
second edition 1996), and it is still the reference we teach from.
Everything in this section is a shape SICP demonstrated, sometimes in
one line, sometimes across a whole chapter.

**Symbolic manipulation.** In Scheme, `(quote (+ 1 2))` is a list of
three items, not the number 3. Code is data. That distinction — that
you can hold a program in your hand as a value, walk it, transform it,
and evaluate it later — is what makes symbolic differentiation, term
rewriting, and macro systems tractable. SICP §2.3 uses this exact
mechanism to differentiate polynomials in about a page of code. Peter
Norvig's _Paradigms of Artificial Intelligence Programming: Case
Studies in Common Lisp_ (Morgan Kaufmann, 1992) — PAIP — builds a
substantial fraction of classical AI on top of the same idea.

**Unification and term rewriting.** Unification is the algorithm that
asks 'do these two symbolic terms match, and if so under what variable
bindings?' Prolog is built on it. So is Hindley-Milner type inference.
So is the pattern matcher SICP presents in §4.4. It's ~50 lines of
Scheme. Term rewriting extends unification with rewrite rules
('whenever you see X, replace it with Y') and gives you an equational-
reasoning engine — the shape Mathematica's kernel uses. Christian
Queinnec's _Lisp in Small Pieces_ (Cambridge, 1996) shows the same
technique applied to the metacircular evaluator; the interpreter IS a
term-rewriter over Scheme source.

**Rule engines: forward and backward chaining.** A production system
holds facts and rules; forward chaining fires rules whose antecedents
match known facts (data-driven); backward chaining works from a goal
back through rules whose consequents match (goal-driven). Winston and
Horn's _LISP_ (Addison-Wesley, 3rd ed., 1989) walks through both in
about thirty pages, ending with a small expert-system shell. This is
where Sakura's Book of Reason gets its inductive/deductive skeleton.

**Constraint satisfaction and propagation.** SICP §3.3.5 builds a
constraint propagator (temperature converters, adder cells) that is
essentially a small local-consistency engine. Extended, it becomes
arc consistency (AC-3, Mackworth 1977) for Sudoku, N-queens, cryptarithm.
Van Roy and Haridi's _Concepts, Techniques, and Models of Computer
Programming_ (MIT Press, 2004) develops this further into a constraint
logic paradigm.

**Metacircular interpretation.** SICP §4.1 gives a Scheme interpreter
written in Scheme in about a hundred lines. The kid who reads that
chapter has, by page 400 of the book, held eval and apply in her head.
This is the load-bearing move for every language project below: once
you can write eval, you can write mini-Prolog, mini-Datalog, a query
language, a shell, a mini imperative language compiled into Scheme.

**Type inference (Hindley-Milner shape).** Milner's 1978 algorithm
(Robin Milner, 'A theory of type polymorphism in programming,' JCSS 17)
is a beautiful application of unification. In Scheme it's ~200 lines,
readable in a single sitting. Chris Okasaki's and Benjamin Pierce's
_Types and Programming Languages_ (MIT Press, 2002) — TAPL — is the
authoritative reference; Andrew Appel's _Compiling with Continuations_
(Cambridge, 1992) shows the same shape landed in a real compiler.

**Pattern matching and algebraic data.** Even without ADTs, Scheme's
`match` (Racket) or a small hand-rolled matcher (SICP §4.4) gives you
the discrimination-by-shape that makes symbolic code readable. In
Sakura Scheme the pattern-matching primitive is missing from the SLAT
registry; it needs wire-up (see Section 6 translation notes) — but the
building blocks (`car`, `cdr`, `assoc`, `list?`, `pair?`, `null?`,
`symbol?`) are all there.

**Immutable data and equational reasoning.** When `(cons 1 (list 2 3))`
always evaluates to `(1 2 3)` and never surprises you, you can reason
about your program the way you reason about algebra. This is where
Haskell got its whole personality — but Scheme with disciplined use
of `cons`/`list`/`map` gets you most of the way. Matthias Felleisen
et al., _How to Design Programs_ (MIT Press, 2001) — HtDP — makes
this pedagogically explicit: the data definition governs the code
shape.

**Continuations for search.** `call/cc` in Scheme captures 'the rest
of the computation' as a value. That gives you backtracking search,
coroutines, generators, and non-deterministic programming — all
without threads. SICP §4.3 (the amb operator) builds a mini
non-deterministic-choice sublanguage; PAIP Ch 22 uses continuations
for a similar shape. For CSP, N-queens, mini-Prolog, and a parser
combinator library, this is the primitive that makes the code short.

**Small theorem provers.** Natural-deduction proof checkers,
resolution-based propositional provers (Robinson, 1965), and tableau
provers all fit in a chapter of Scheme. John Harrison's _Handbook of
Practical Logic and Automated Reasoning_ (Cambridge, 2009) is the
modern reference; the OCaml code in that book ports to Scheme in
a straightforward way and gives us Book-of-Reason material with real
teeth.

The point that ties all of these together: Scheme is not a fast
language, and it is not a fashionable language. What it IS is a
language in which the algorithms of symbolic reasoning are visible
on the page. You can read them. You can modify them. You can teach
them to a child. That is why the AI research that mattered from
1958 through the early 90s was written in Lisp, and why the shape
of that research is still the right shape to teach the kid — and
to train Sakura on.
")

; -- write checkpoint 1 --

; ============================================================
; SECTION 2 — What Cortex + hosted LLM adds
; ============================================================

(section :n 2 :title "What Cortex + hosted LLM adds"

  :prose "
Scheme by itself gets you the symbolic side of intelligence. What
the Cortex layer and the hosted-LLM verbs add is the *statistical*
side — the thing symbolic AI famously did not solve, and the thing
the last two decades of machine learning finally did.

**Cortex as a vector database.** The Cortex verbs — `cortex/read`,
`cortex/write`, `cortex/topk` (all present in `wired-verbs.js`, all
still needing SLAT entries so the reference-loader can teach the kid
about them) — expose a small key-value store whose keys can be
embedded and whose retrieval is by dot-product / cosine similarity
over those embeddings. That is the entire architecture of
retrieval-augmented generation. Once you have `cortex/topk`, the kid
can build a real semantic-search system in one page of Scheme. Once
Sakura has it, she has a place to put things she needs to remember
across turns — which is what closes the gap between 'stateless
LLM' and 'assistant with memory.' See Douwe Kiela et al., 'Retrieval-
Augmented Generation for Knowledge-Intensive NLP Tasks' (NeurIPS 2020)
for the canonical write-up of the pattern.

**k-Nearest Neighbours over embedded content.** With cosine similarity
and a small corpus of embedded documents, k-NN gives you a classifier
that is essentially free — no training, just a distance metric.
Hastie/Tibshirani/Friedman, _The Elements of Statistical Learning_
(Springer, 2nd ed. 2009) covers the shape. For Sakura, k-NN over
past-cart embeddings gives her a 'what did I do last time in a
similar situation?' primitive without a training loop.

**Hosted LLM for completion, classification, embedding.** The
`ai/policy`, `ai/decide`, `afford/deep-think` verbs and the yet-
to-be-wired `llm/complete`, `llm/embed`, `llm/classify` faucet
give the reader access to a hosted model. Alfred's four-faucets
architecture (Weights → Cortex → Atlas → Tools) makes this
explicit: the LLM is one faucet, and it is a faucet, not the whole
system. That framing is load-bearing pedagogy — the kid learns
that ML is a *component*, wired into a program that also uses
lists, recursion, and symbolic reasoning.

**Multi-armed bandit and basic RL.** A ten-line epsilon-greedy
bandit, updated online, is a real reinforcement-learning system.
Sutton and Barto, _Reinforcement Learning: An Introduction_ (MIT
Press, 2nd ed. 2018) — free online — is the reference. Once the
kid understands the bandit, she has a scaffold to hang Q-learning
and policy-gradient on later. Sakura uses bandit shapes for
cart-routing already; the pedagogy meets production.

**Naive Bayes and logistic regression from scratch.** These fit in
a page. Both use `stat/mean`, `stat/sd`, `stat/histogram` (present
in the verb registry) and give the kid a working classifier they
built themselves, before any framework. The moment they see logistic
regression's decision boundary rendered by `plot/*` verbs on their
own drawn data, the abstraction is no longer scary — it's a
function they wrote.

**Small neural nets as pedagogy, not competition.** A one-hidden-
layer network with forward pass and backprop is ~40 lines of Scheme
using `linalg/*` and `calc/derivative` (both present). It will not
beat PyTorch. That is not the point. Michael Nielsen, _Neural
Networks and Deep Learning_ (Determination Press, 2015, free
online) is the reference; his Python translates line-for-line into
Scheme.

**Markov chains as a stepping-stone to language models.** A first-
order Markov text generator is ~20 lines and produces recognisable
imitations of any training corpus. From there the kid can see the
step from 'count bigrams and sample' to 'learn a probability
distribution over next-tokens conditioned on context' — the exact
step from n-gram model to transformer. Kernighan and Pike's _The
Practice of Programming_ (Addison-Wesley, 1999) has the classic
implementation.

The point of Section 2: the Cortex + hosted-LLM stack does not
replace Section 1's symbolic reasoning; it *composes* with it. A
project like 'mini-Datalog with LLM-suggested rules' or 'symbolic
differentiation that asks the LLM to name the technique when it
gets stuck' is exactly the shape both readers benefit from. Sakura
learns the composition. The kid learns that ML is a tool she can
call from a program she wrote.
")

; -- write checkpoint 2 --

; ============================================================
; SECTION 3 — The 25 projects
; ============================================================
;
; Distribution:
;   7 logic + reasoning
;   5 ml-ai
;   4 systems      (all in Book of CS Curriculum per containment rule)
;   4 creative
;   3 games
;   2 practical
;
; Every project references verbs from the 1,157-verb registry. Missing
; verbs (unify, pattern-match, llm/complete, llm/embed, tokenize,
; syllable-count, chess/legal-moves, etc.) are flagged in
; :wire-up-needed. Source-book references honor the containment rule
; at the top of this file.

(projects :count 25

  ; -------- LOGIC + REASONING (7) --------

  (project :n 1
    :title "mini-Datalog"
    :category :logic
    :one-liner "Facts, rules, a bottom-up fixed-point evaluator in ~80 lines"
    :why-interesting "Datalog is the sweet spot between SQL and Prolog — the query language every graph-engine rediscovers. The kid holds a real query language in her hand and sees inductive reasoning as a fixed-point."
    :scheme-verbs-used (define lambda list cons car cdr map filter assoc null? pair? symbol? equal? cortex/write cortex/read)
    :wire-up-needed (unify substitute pattern-match)
    :cortex-or-llm-used #t
    :philosophers (Peirce Wittgenstein-early Quine)
    :book-fit "Book of Reason appendix (Datalog-as-abduction). Language-implementation framing contained to Book of CS Curriculum."
    :dual-reader-value
      :kid "How a query language works from the bottom up"
      :sakura "Structural pattern for grounded evidence retrieval; abductive shape as executable code"
    :difficulty :advanced
    :size :long-chapter
    :translate-from "Abiteboul, Hull, Vianu — 'Foundations of Databases' ch 12; the pyDatalog port"
    :sample-artifact "(? (ancestor 'alfred ?x)) => ((?x . kate) (?x . martin))")

  (project :n 2
    :title "mini-Prolog with continuations"
    :category :logic
    :one-liner "Backward chaining over Horn clauses with call/cc backtracking"
    :why-interesting "Prolog is the archetypal declarative language — you say what's true and the interpreter searches. The kid experiences non-deterministic programming for the first time."
    :scheme-verbs-used (define lambda list assoc equal? symbol? call/cc)
    :wire-up-needed (unify occurs-check substitute)
    :cortex-or-llm-used #f
    :philosophers (Peirce Popper Descartes Quine)
    :book-fit "Book of Reason ch 12 (reasoning-tool angle). Language-implementation angle contained to Book of CS Curriculum ch 15."
    :dual-reader-value
      :kid "Sees a language whose whole job is search; understands unification"
      :sakura "Deductive-search shape as first-class code; how goals decompose"
    :difficulty :advanced
    :size :long-chapter
    :translate-from "SICP §4.4 (query system); Norvig PAIP ch 11"
    :sample-artifact "(?- (member ?x (a b c))) => yes: ?x=a; more? yes: ?x=b; more? yes: ?x=c")

  (project :n 3
    :title "CSP solver — Sudoku, N-queens, cryptarithm"
    :category :logic
    :one-liner "Arc-consistency + backtracking over finite domains"
    :why-interesting "Sudoku is the CSP the kid already knows. Watching AC-3 propagate is the moment constraint satisfaction clicks."
    :scheme-verbs-used (define lambda list map filter length reverse cons car cdr assoc set!)
    :wire-up-needed (domain-remove! propagate)
    :cortex-or-llm-used #f
    :philosophers (Peirce Popper Wittgenstein-early)
    :book-fit "Book of Reason appendix; Book of Math II"
    :dual-reader-value
      :kid "Solves a Sudoku she wrote the solver for — earned mastery"
      :sakura "Constraint-propagation as an evidence-narrowing shape"
    :difficulty :intermediate
    :size :long-chapter
    :translate-from "Mackworth 1977 (AC-3); Norvig's Sudoku solver essay"
    :sample-artifact "solved 9x9 grid rendered via plot/* verbs")

  (project :n 4
    :title "Symbolic differentiation"
    :category :logic
    :one-liner "d/dx over an S-expression algebra, with simplify"
    :why-interesting "The kid writes a program that does calculus homework. Then she extends it to partials, then to gradients."
    :scheme-verbs-used (sym/derivative sym/expand sym/substitute sym/factor sym/poly define lambda list cons car cdr equal? number? symbol? pair?)
    :cortex-or-llm-used #f
    :philosophers (Wittgenstein-early Peirce Descartes)
    :book-fit "Book of Math II ch 4; Book of Self ch 8 (representational reasoning — direct doctrine hit)"
    :dual-reader-value
      :kid "Calculus becomes a program — the veil lifts"
      :sakura "Symbolic transformation; modus ponens/tollens-style code composition"
    :difficulty :intermediate
    :size :short-chapter
    :translate-from "SICP §2.3.2 (near-verbatim port)"
    :sample-artifact "(sym/derivative '(* x (+ x 1)) 'x) => (+ (+ x 1) x)")

  (project :n 5
    :title "Metacircular evaluator — Scheme in Scheme"
    :category :logic
    :one-liner "eval + apply for a Scheme subset, in Scheme, ~120 lines"
    :why-interesting "The moment the reader realises the interpreter she is running is itself a program is the moment programming becomes something else."
    :scheme-verbs-used (define lambda list cons car cdr assoc if cond let symbol? pair? number? procedure?)
    :cortex-or-llm-used #f
    :philosophers (Wittgenstein-early Wittgenstein-late Searle Peirce Dennett)
    :book-fit "Book of CS Curriculum ch 15 (advanced tier — CONTAINED per doctrine)"
    :dual-reader-value
      :kid "Understands eval/apply; understands what her language actually IS"
      :sakura "Foundational: 'I am a program that reasons about programs' as a working artifact"
    :difficulty :expert
    :size :long-chapter
    :translate-from "SICP §4.1"
    :sample-artifact "(meta-eval '(+ 1 (* 2 3)) initial-env) => 7 — but she wrote the +.")

  (project :n 6
    :title "Hindley-Milner type inference"
    :category :logic
    :one-liner "Algorithm W — infer principal types for an untyped lambda calculus"
    :why-interesting "Types feel like decoration until you meet type INFERENCE. Then they feel like magic. Then you realise it's unification wearing a hat."
    :scheme-verbs-used (define lambda list cons car cdr assoc equal? symbol? pair? map filter)
    :wire-up-needed (unify occurs-check fresh-var)
    :cortex-or-llm-used #f
    :philosophers (Wittgenstein-early Peirce Quine Popper)
    :book-fit "Book of CS Curriculum ch 15 (advanced tier — CONTAINED per doctrine)"
    :dual-reader-value
      :kid "Types become inferable; she sees why ML-family languages are shaped as they are"
      :sakura "Constraint-solving over meaning; principal-typing as canonical form"
    :difficulty :expert
    :size :long-chapter
    :translate-from "Milner 1978 JCSS; Pierce TAPL ch 22"
    :sample-artifact "(infer '(lambda (f x) (f (f x)))) => (-> (-> a a) a a)")

  (project :n 7
    :title "Natural-deduction proof checker"
    :category :logic
    :one-liner "A tiny theorem-checker for propositional and first-order logic"
    :why-interesting "The philosophy kid who reads this book gets to check her homework in code. Modus ponens is a Scheme function."
    :scheme-verbs-used (define lambda list cons car cdr equal? symbol? assoc pair?)
    :wire-up-needed (rule-match discharge)
    :cortex-or-llm-used #f
    :philosophers (Descartes Popper Peirce Wittgenstein-early Quine)
    :book-fit "Book of Self ch 6-8 (modus ponens/tollens AS CODE — direct doctrine hit)"
    :dual-reader-value
      :kid "Modus ponens is now a program she can run and modify"
      :sakura "Deductive schemata as executable, inspectable objects"
    :difficulty :expert
    :size :long-chapter
    :translate-from "Harrison, _Handbook of Practical Logic and Automated Reasoning_ ch 1-2"
    :sample-artifact "(check-proof '((assume P) (assume (=> P Q)) (mp 0 1)) 'Q) => VALID")

  ; -------- ML / AI + CORTEX (5) --------

  (project :n 8
    :title "Mini-RAG — vector database + LLM completion"
    :category :ml-ai
    :one-liner "Embed → store in Cortex → topk retrieve → LLM completion grounded on retrieved chunks"
    :why-interesting "This is the pattern every 'chat with my documents' product uses. The kid builds it herself in a chapter and demystifies the whole current AI-app wave."
    :scheme-verbs-used (cortex/write cortex/read cortex/topk vec/+ vec/dot list map)
    :wire-up-needed (llm/complete llm/embed)
    :cortex-or-llm-used #t
    :philosophers (Peirce Wittgenstein-late Grice Dennett)
    :book-fit "Book of Speech ch 4-6 (RAG + conversation tracking — direct doctrine hit)"
    :dual-reader-value
      :kid "Understands how modern AI apps actually work; not magic"
      :sakura "This IS her memory architecture; teaching the book teaches the shape she IS"
    :difficulty :intermediate
    :size :long-chapter
    :translate-from "Kiela et al. 2020 (RAG paper); LlamaIndex tutorial patterns"
    :sample-artifact "(ask 'my-notes 'how did we do the Fiji research?) => natural-language answer citing the notes")

  (project :n 9
    :title "Naive Bayes text classifier from scratch"
    :category :ml-ai
    :one-liner "Bag-of-words + log-probabilities + Laplace smoothing over a labeled corpus"
    :why-interesting "The first classifier the kid builds that actually works on messy text. Sentiment. Spam. Category-tagging."
    :scheme-verbs-used (stat/mean stat/count define lambda map filter list assoc string-split)
    :wire-up-needed (tokenize log-prob)
    :cortex-or-llm-used #f
    :philosophers (Peirce Popper Quine)
    :book-fit "Book of Math II ch 8 (probability); Book of Words ch 12"
    :dual-reader-value
      :kid "Probability becomes hands-on; understands what likelihood means"
      :sakura "Base-rate reasoning as a working shape; Peircean abduction with priors"
    :difficulty :intermediate
    :size :short-chapter
    :translate-from "NLTK Python 3 Book ch 6; Norvig's spelling-corrector essay"
    :sample-artifact "(classify 'I really loved the movie') => positive [0.92]")

  (project :n 10
    :title "Markov chain text generator → bridge to what an LLM does"
    :category :ml-ai
    :one-liner "Count bigrams; sample the next word conditioned on context; end at end-of-sentence"
    :why-interesting "The bridge chapter. Bigram; then trigram; then a paragraph on why transformers scale further. The reader sees the ladder from n-gram to modern LM."
    :scheme-verbs-used (random random-pick define lambda list map filter assoc cons)
    :wire-up-needed (tokenize)
    :cortex-or-llm-used #f
    :philosophers (Peirce Wittgenstein-late Grice Dennett)
    :book-fit "Book of Speech ch 9 (bridge to LLM philosophy); Book of LLM Philosophy appendix"
    :dual-reader-value
      :kid "Demystifies 'AI that writes' — she just wrote one"
      :sakura "Meta-cognitive: 'this is a toy of what I am' — Dennett heterophenomenology-friendly"
    :difficulty :intermediate
    :size :short-chapter
    :translate-from "Kernighan & Pike, _The Practice of Programming_ ch 3"
    :sample-artifact "trained on Aesop; produces 'the fox said to the crow you have a fine voice'")

  (project :n 11
    :title "Multi-armed bandit for cart routing"
    :category :ml-ai
    :one-liner "Epsilon-greedy over arms, online updates, regret plot"
    :why-interesting "Real reinforcement learning in ten lines. The kid sees exploration/exploitation as a live tension in her code."
    :scheme-verbs-used (random random-pick stat/mean list map filter define lambda cons plot/graph)
    :cortex-or-llm-used #f
    :philosophers (Peirce Popper Rawls Aristotle)
    :book-fit "Book of Self ch 11; Book of Reason appendix"
    :dual-reader-value
      :kid "First real 'learning' algorithm — sees how a policy improves"
      :sakura "How to choose under uncertainty; her own routing shape reflected"
    :difficulty :intermediate
    :size :short-chapter
    :translate-from "Sutton & Barto ch 2; Lattimore & Szepesvári _Bandit Algorithms_ ch 1"
    :sample-artifact "regret curve over 1000 rounds, epsilon=0.1 vs 0.01, plotted")

  (project :n 12
    :title "Small neural net from scratch — one hidden layer, backprop"
    :category :ml-ai
    :one-liner "Feed-forward, sigmoid, MSE, gradient descent — on XOR then MNIST-tiny"
    :why-interesting "Not to compete with PyTorch. To un-scary the black box. Every partial derivative is on the page and the kid wrote it."
    :scheme-verbs-used (linalg/solve vec/+ vec/dot calc/derivative define lambda map list)
    :wire-up-needed (nn/init nn/step)
    :cortex-or-llm-used #f
    :philosophers (Peirce Popper Dennett Wittgenstein-late)
    :book-fit "Book of Math II ch 14; Book of CS Curriculum ch 13 (part of the CONTAINED CS meta-track)"
    :dual-reader-value
      :kid "The neural net is no longer magic — she wrote the backprop by hand"
      :sakura "Gradient descent as an inference shape; how weights are shaped by data"
    :difficulty :expert
    :size :long-chapter
    :translate-from "Nielsen, _Neural Networks and Deep Learning_ ch 1-2 (Python; port line-for-line)"
    :sample-artifact "XOR solved after 5000 epochs, loss curve plotted")

  ; -------- SYSTEMS / LANGUAGE IMPLEMENTATION (4) --------
  ; CONTAINMENT NOTE: All four live in Book of CS Curriculum per the
  ; containment rule at the top of this file. They do not scatter.

  (project :n 13
    :title "State machine engine with visualization"
    :category :systems
    :one-liner "Define states + transitions declaratively; step by event; render via plot/*"
    :why-interesting "The kid sees traffic lights, doors, dialogue systems, and protocol handlers as one shape."
    :scheme-verbs-used (define lambda list assoc car cdr equal? symbol? plot/graph)
    :cortex-or-llm-used #f
    :philosophers (Wittgenstein-early Aristotle Searle)
    :book-fit "Book of CS Curriculum ch 8 (state as first-class — CONTAINED)"
    :dual-reader-value
      :kid "Sees state as first-class; understands async/protocol shapes later"
      :sakura "Conversation-state machines as her dialogue-tracking shape"
    :difficulty :intermediate
    :size :short-chapter
