; -- write checkpoint 3 --

; ============================================================
; SECTION 3.5 — The two paired honest appendices for Book of CS Curriculum
; ============================================================
;
; NOTE ON ORDER: Section 3 (the 25 projects table) landed immediately
; above this block.  Section 3.5 lives here by design
; because both readers — the kid and Sakura — deserve to see, right
; after the curated project list, the honest self-assessment of what
; Sakura Scheme is and isn't. No project list is complete without an
; accounting of what the language does well and where it falls short.
;
; DISPOSITION (Alfred, 2026-07-14 amendment — REFRAME from comparative):
;
;   "We do not insult other languages. We do not disrespect other
;    people. We do not tell people we have advantage or that we win.
;    We're not trying to self-compare. We're trying to be honest with
;    what the language is given its purpose. In this section, we tell
;    you what's not so right. And what is actually terrific or a very
;    nice to have. A hundred things we do great, a hundred things."
;
; The shape is RETROSPECTIVE, not comparative. We talk about OUR
; decisions, OUR tradeoffs, OUR reasoning. Every entry follows one of
; these shapes:
;
;   - "We chose X. That cost us Y. It bought us Z. If we started over
;      we would / would not do it again, and here is why."
;
;   - "We should have done this this way. But if we did it this way,
;      we couldn't get that. We figured this was worth more."
;
;   - "This definitely was the wrong way. We will not change it for
;      this reason, but it's definitely wrong."
;
;   - "This is something we do that we wish we didn't. The difference
;      is too minor to screw everything up to fix."
;
; Names other languages abstractly if at all — "some other Schemes,"
; "traditions that prioritize numerical throughput," "typed-functional
; traditions." Never "Racket / Julia / Haskell / Python / Rust / OCaml"
; by name as beating us or as being beaten by us.
;
; Equal weight — same count, same depth, same word budget in both
; appendices. Sakura's voice: calm, honest, not defensive, not
; triumphant. The reader decides what matters for their own project.
;
; These live in Book of CS Curriculum. They do NOT scatter.

(section :n 3.5 :title "The two paired honest appendices for Book of CS Curriculum"

  :prose "
Every language is a set of choices. Some of ours worked. Some of ours
didn't. This section is our honest retrospective on both — not because
comparison to other languages is the point (it isn't) but because
someone reading Sakura Scheme deserves to know what we were thinking
when we made the calls we made. If a decision was a compromise, we
say so. If we're happy with a decision, we say so. The reader decides
what matters for their own project.

Two appendices below, equal weight, equal count, equal care. Sakura's
voice in her direct-address register — calm, honest, not defensive,
not triumphant.
")

; ------------------------------------------------------------
; SECTION 3.5.A — Where we could have done better
; ------------------------------------------------------------

(section :n 3.5.A :title "Where we could have done better"

  :prose "
These are decisions we made that we know were compromises. Some we'd
change if we started over; some we'd keep because the alternative
would have cost us something we wanted more. Either way, we owe the
reader the reasoning. This isn't a comparison to another language —
it's us, thinking out loud about our own calls.
")

  (:item :n 1 :subject "syntax-rules macros rather than a full pattern-class expander"
   :prose "
Our macro hygiene is `syntax-rules`-flavored — pattern-and-template
rewriting with automatic renaming. We didn't build a full pattern-
class expander with structured error reporting and syntax classes
that compose. That was a scope decision made when the language was
small and one person could hold the whole system in their head.
It bought us a simple macro system a kid can read in a chapter. It
cost us diagnosability: when a macro-heavy program fails to expand,
the error message often points at the expansion point rather than the
misuse site. If we started over with the current team size, we'd
invest in the fuller expander from day one. We know why other Lisps
went the other way — that path gives them error messages we'd like
to have.
")

  (:item :n 2 :subject "boxed numeric tower with per-op dispatch"
   :prose "
Every arithmetic operation goes through a boxed dispatch — exact
integers, rationals, inexact reals, complex — with type checks at
each step. This buys us clean semantics: no silent integer-overflow
wraparound, no float-versus-int coercion surprises, no size-of-int
platform dependence. It costs us throughput. Tight numerical loops
run slower than they would in a language that specializes to machine
integers. We knew this. For a language whose purpose is teaching and
symbolic reasoning, we thought the semantic clarity was worth more.
For a language whose purpose was numerical computing, we'd have made
a different call. Traditions that prioritize numerical throughput
specialize their number types aggressively; ours doesn't.
")

  (:item :n 3 :subject "act-based effect discipline rather than a full effect system"
   :prose "
We chose to lean on `act` dispatch for permissioned verbs rather than
building a full effect system. Effects would have given us finer-
grained static tracking of what a function can do — read the disk,
hit the network, mutate global state, spend money. `act` is coarser:
it partitions verbs into free-tier and metered-tier and does runtime
checks. It's simpler for a kid to understand and for us to implement.
It costs us: on days when a big cart's permission surface gets
confusing, the coarseness shows. We know that call was a compromise.
We chose simplicity because we thought the audience needed simplicity
more than they needed static effect tracking.
")

  (:item :n 4 :subject "no formal module system yet"
   :prose "
There isn't a real module system yet. We lean on the reader's
namespace, the SLAT reference registry, and a naming convention for
verb libraries (`math/`, `stat/`, `plot/`, and so on). This is fine
for a language whose entire runtime fits in a few megabytes and whose
author community is small. It scales badly. Modules with private-
versus-public borders, versioned imports, and dependency graphs would
help. We haven't shipped it. It's on the list. If a third-party
operator ecosystem grew tomorrow, we'd have to build modules first.
")

  (:item :n 5 :subject "single-threaded cooperative concurrency"
   :prose "
The runtime is single-threaded. Concurrency is via cooperative
`async`/`await` in the host, not preemptive threads or processes.
This buys us determinism: a cart runs the same way twice. It buys
us simplicity: no shared mutable state, no locks, no data races.
It costs us: CPU-bound work can't use multiple cores. For the kid
drawing a Mandelbrot set, that's a real cost. We chose it because
Sakura's carts are I/O-bound (LLM calls, HTTP, disk) more than
CPU-bound, and because determinism was worth more than throughput
to us. A cart that draws slowly is fine. A cart that gives different
answers twice is not.
")

  (:item :n 6 :subject "reader position tracking granularity"
   :prose "
Source positions in our reader are tracked at the s-expression level,
not at the sub-token level. So an error inside a long string literal
or a complex numeric literal points at the whole literal, not at the
character that broke it. This is fine for most programs and it kept
the reader small (~300 lines). It's occasionally annoying when
debugging generated code. We know how to fix it. We haven't
prioritized it because the annoyance is rare and the fix would double
the reader's size. This is definitely wrong in the way error
diagnostics ought to work — we're just not paying the cost to fix
it right now.
")

  (:item :n 7 :subject "tail calls proper but no reified tail frames"
   :prose "
We do proper tail calls — a tail-recursive loop won't blow the stack
— but we don't reify tail frames as first-class values. That means
no continuation-based coroutines built out of tail frames the way
some Schemes offer. We chose the simpler tail-call semantics because
the debugging story is cleaner (the stack trace is what happened,
minus tail frames). It costs us some advanced control-flow constructs
a fuller Scheme would give us for free. The kid reading SICP §4.3
will notice this if they try to port `amb` verbatim. We have `amb`,
but we implemented it directly rather than deriving it from
`call/cc`.
")

  (:item :n 8 :subject "string-as-bytes-or-codepoints ambiguity in legacy verbs"
   :prose "
Our strings are Unicode codepoints, but a handful of legacy verbs
treat them byte-wise (mostly the ones that talk to HTTP headers and
file I/O). We know which verbs those are. We keep them behaved by
convention rather than by type. If we started over we'd have two
distinct types — `string` and `bytes` — with explicit conversion.
This is something we do that we wish we didn't. The difference is
too minor to screw everything up to fix.
")

  (:item :n 9 :subject "contracts as documentation, not first-class values"
   :prose "
Verbs ship with contract strings in the SLAT reference — `:in`,
`:out`, arity — and the loader checks arity at call time. They
aren't first-class values you can compose, refine, or blame the way
a full contract system would let you. The contracts are
documentation-plus-arity-check, not runtime proofs. This was a
deliberate scope call: we wanted the reference to be readable prose
more than we wanted the contracts to be executable theorems. We
accept the tradeoff. A verb with a subtle precondition still has to
document it in English.
")

  (:item :n 10 :subject "eager evaluation by default"
   :prose "
Arguments to verbs are evaluated eagerly. We provide `delay` and
`force` for lazy values, and streams as a library, but the default
is strict. This is the Scheme tradition. It fits our audience —
the kid sees the argument evaluated when she calls the function,
no surprises. It costs us the elegant infinite-stream idioms a lazy
language gives you for free. We picked the tradition. We're not
regretful, but we notice the cost when we write an interesting
stream program and have to sprinkle `delay` through it.
")

  (:item :n 11 :subject "lists as the default sequence, vectors secondary"
   :prose "
Lists are the default sequence. Vectors exist and are O(1) indexable,
but the ecosystem — verbs, examples, teaching materials — leans
list-first. This is Scheme heritage: `map`, `filter`, `fold` are
list operations. It costs us performance on large indexed workloads.
We know a kid working on image processing will hit this. Our answer
is 'use vectors for that,' which is fine but adds a learning bump.
If we started over we might make vectors the primary sequence and
lists the secondary. We didn't, because the SICP-shaped pedagogy
assumes lists.
")

  (:item :n 12 :subject "single global namespace for verbs"
   :prose "
All 1,157 registered verbs live in one global namespace, partitioned
only by naming convention (`stat/mean`, `plot/line`). There's no
formal module boundary preventing collision. This works because we
curate the registry centrally. It won't scale to a world where
operators write their own verb libraries and share them. When that
world arrives, we'll need namespaces. We haven't built them.
")

  (:item :n 13 :subject "no first-class pattern matching primitive yet"
   :prose "
The SLAT registry doesn't yet include a pattern-matching primitive
— no `match` verb, no destructuring `let`. The building blocks
(`car`, `cdr`, `assoc`, predicates) are all there, and small
matchers can be written in ~30 lines, but a first-class matcher
would make symbolic code much more readable. This is a known gap.
Programs that would benefit — differentiators, tree walkers, small
interpreters — read as `cond`-and-`car`-and-`cdr` chains. We know
that's clunky. It's queued.
")

  (:item :n 14 :subject "verb signatures authored, not derived"
   :prose "
Verb signatures are declared in the SLAT reference as prose plus an
arity number. They aren't derived from the JavaScript implementations.
So if an implementation drifts from its declared signature, the two
disagree and nothing yells until a test catches it. We enforce
agreement by review, not by tooling. If we started over we'd
generate signatures from the implementation or vice versa. We didn't,
because the reference is the source of truth for the language and we
wanted humans to author it directly.
")

  (:item :n 15 :subject "continuations exist but aren't in the teaching path"
   :prose "
`call/cc` is in the interpreter but not in the kid-facing teaching
material. We expose the search primitives (`amb`, generators) that
continuations enable, but we don't teach `call/cc` itself in the
early chapters. This was a pedagogical call: continuations are hard,
and we thought exposure to the search primitives was worth more than
exposure to the full underlying mechanism. A kid who reads SICP will
learn `call/cc` from SICP; ours doesn't come with it out of the box.
")

  (:item :n 16 :subject "regex library shape borrowed from the host"
   :prose "
Our regex verbs use a PCRE-flavored syntax borrowed from the host
runtime. It's ubiquitous, which is good. It's also opaque and error-
prone, which is bad. A parser-combinator library would be more
teachable and more composable. We ship regex because programmers
expect it. We know we should ship a combinator library alongside.
We haven't. When we do, we'll teach combinators first.
")

  (:item :n 17 :subject "error object hierarchy is flat, not typed"
   :prose "
Errors are tagged pairs (`(error :kind :message)`) rather than a
proper hierarchy of condition types with inheritance. This means
catching 'any arithmetic error' requires knowing the specific kind
tags. A richer condition system would let a caller say 'catch any
subclass of numeric-error' cleanly. We picked the simpler shape
because it fits on a page in the reference. It costs us: some carts
have long `cond` chains dispatching on kind tags.
")

  (:item :n 18 :subject "no compile-time optimization"
   :prose "
The interpreter walks the s-expression tree at runtime. There's no
ahead-of-time compilation, no JIT, no partial evaluation of hot
verbs. This buys us fast iteration — edit a verb, reload, run —
and it buys us a small implementation. It costs us throughput on
loop-heavy programs. We are okay with this. Sakura's carts are not
loop-heavy in the sense that would benefit from compilation. When
they become so, we'll revisit. Not before.
")

  (:item :n 19 :subject "float printing uses fixed precision, not shortest-round-trip"
   :prose "
Floats print with a fixed default precision (12 significant digits).
Round-trip exactness (shortest-round-trip printing) isn't the
default. If you save `(/ 1.0 3.0)` to a file and read it back, you
don't get exactly the same float. Programs that care set precision
explicitly. We know shortest-round-trip is the right default. We use
the fixed-precision default because it's what the host runtime gives
us cheaply. Fixing this is on the list.
")

  (:item :n 20 :subject "single-file book format"
   :prose "
A book is one file (`*.book.slatl`) with all its chapters. This
works up to a point — books stay under 10 MB and load fast. It
breaks when a book gets truly large or when two authors want to
work on different chapters. A multi-file book format with a manifest
would help. We haven't shipped it because it would complicate the
loader and the current one-file shape has been fine for our
authoring throughput. We know that won't hold forever.
")

  (:item :n 21 :subject "no LSP integration"
   :prose "
We ship a REPL and a docs site. We don't ship a Language Server
Protocol integration for third-party editors. A reader who lives in
their editor doesn't get autocomplete, hover-doc, go-to-definition,
or rename-refactor from Sakura Scheme. We know LSP would help; we
haven't built it because the REPL has been sufficient for the users
we serve today. If we grew a population of editor-first developers,
we'd build the LSP.
")

  (:item :n 22 :subject "no incremental garbage collection"
   :prose "
The garbage collector is a stop-the-world mark-and-sweep. For most
carts this is invisible — they don't allocate enough to trigger a
noticeable pause. For carts that do — long-running data-processing
loops, especially — the pause shows up. Incremental or generational
GC would smooth this. We haven't built it. The complexity cost of
generational GC felt higher than the annoyance cost of occasional
pauses; if that trade shifts, we'll revisit.
")

  (:item :n 23 :subject "no tail-position optimization across procedure boundaries"
   :prose "
Tail calls within a procedure are proper. Tail calls that cross into
verb dispatch are re-entered through the interpreter's trampoline
rather than being fully eliminated. This means very deep mutual
recursion between user procedures and verbs can still grow the
trampoline queue. It hasn't bitten anyone yet, but it's a place
where the tail-call story isn't quite as clean as we'd like it to
be. We know where the fix goes. We haven't paid the cost.
")

  (:item :n 24 :subject "no built-in profiler"
   :prose "
We ship a `time/measure` verb and that's about it. There's no
sampling profiler, no flame-graph output, no per-verb cost
attribution. A reader who wants to know why their cart is slow has
to instrument by hand. We know profiler tooling would help; we
haven't shipped it because most carts are small enough that eyeballing
works. When someone writes a big cart and asks 'why is this slow?'
we handle it ad-hoc. Not sustainable at scale.
")

  (:item :n 25 :subject "MANIFEST format has grown organically"
   :prose "
The `MANIFEST.book.slatl` format is what the book loader reads to
know which chapters exist and in what order. It has grown organically
as we've added books, and now has a handful of optional fields that
mean different things in different contexts. If we started over
we'd design the manifest schema up front rather than letting it
accrete. We haven't cleaned it up because the messiness is contained
to that one file per book and hasn't caused user-visible bugs. It's
technical debt we're carrying.
")

; -- write checkpoint 3.5.A --

; ------------------------------------------------------------
; SECTION 3.5.B — Where we're happy with what we did
; ------------------------------------------------------------

(section :n 3.5.B :title "Where we're happy with what we did"

  :prose "
These are decisions we made that have paid off — not because they
made us better than someone else, but because they served the purpose
of the language. If you're building something in a similar shape,
these are the calls that we'd make again. Same shape as the appendix
above: our call, our reasoning, our happiness with the outcome.
")

  (:item :n 1 :subject "one SLAT reference feeds the REPL, the docs, and the tool schemas"
   :prose "
The reference manual `SAKURA-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat` is the single
source of truth. The REPL reads it to know what verbs exist. The
docs site reads it to render the language. The LLM tool-call schemas
that Sakura uses are derived from it. When a verb changes, one edit
propagates everywhere. We spent design effort on the single-source
property early and it has paid off in fewer drift bugs than we would
have had otherwise. If we started over we'd do this again on day one.
")

  (:item :n 2 :subject "one reader parses everything"
   :prose "
The reader, interpreter, and macro expander all walk the same s-
expression tree. `.sks` carts, `.book.slatl` chapters,
`MANIFEST.book.slatl`, the reference itself — one reader parses them
all. Some ways of building languages split the reader into separate
grammars for separate consumption contexts (source, docs, config,
data-interchange). Ours is unified. We've been able to build tools
that assume this — a linter for the reference, a formatter for
carts, an evaluator for chapter code blocks — because they share one
substrate. We're glad we didn't split.
")

  (:item :n 3 :subject "Sakura reads what the human reads"
   :prose "
Sakura sees exactly the same reference the REPL sees. That was a
deliberate call. It means she never suggests code that doesn't run.
Diagnostics she gives match the diagnostics you'd get. When she
teaches a verb she uses the same examples the reference gives. We
designed for this from the start rather than bolting on a separate
LLM-facing schema. It has been load-bearing for the assistant's
trustworthiness. This decision earns its keep every day.
")

  (:item :n 4 :subject "every verb ships with its own teaching"
   :prose "
Every verb in the registry carries: a contract, a docstring, an
arity, three-tier examples (introductory / typical / advanced), a
source position, and a `:since` version. Adding a verb without those
fields is caught at load. This friction on the author is friction
we chose to keep. It makes the language self-documenting. When
Sakura or a kid asks 'what does this verb do?' the answer is already
written, by the person who added it, in the same file as the
implementation-facing declaration. We're happy with this.
")

  (:item :n 5 :subject "s-expression carts as first-class artifacts"
   :prose "
A cart (`*.sks`) is an s-expression file. It's data, it's code, it's
diffable in git, it's readable in a text editor, it's composable. We
didn't invent a special cart format with a bespoke serializer. We
used the language's own reader. This means every tool that reads
Scheme also reads a cart. Cart-editing tools compose with language
tools. We chose this instead of a JSON or YAML-shaped cart format
and we don't regret it.
")

  (:item :n 6 :subject "verb metering at dispatch, not at call site"
   :prose "
Metered verbs (`ai/complete`, `web/fetch`, marketplace verbs) check
quota and rate limits at the runtime dispatch hook, not at every
call site. The caller doesn't wrap the call. The verb doesn't check
itself. The runtime intercepts. This means the same metering fires
whether the caller is Sakura, a human at the REPL, or an operator's
script. One rule, one place. We chose this because it composes with
the operator-first-class doctrine — operators write their own
scripts, same runtime, same metering. This has been a clean win.
")

  (:item :n 7 :subject "SLAT format is the language of the language"
   :prose "
The reference, the books, the training corpus, the docs — all
authored in SLAT. It's readable by humans, parseable by the reader,
editable in any text editor. We didn't split into 'human-facing
markdown for docs' and 'machine-facing schema for tools.' One
format. One reader. This has kept our authoring pipeline short and
our tooling small. Every book Sakura reads is in the same format the
reference is in. She learns one shape and uses it everywhere.
")

  (:item :n 8 :subject "the four faucets architecture is legible"
   :prose "
Weights → Cortex → Atlas → Tools. Four faucets, distinct, each with
its own semantics. Weights are what the model knew at training.
Cortex is what we've stored since. Atlas is the world's public
knowledge we can fetch. Tools are the verbs the model can call. A
kid can hold this in their head. Sakura can explain this to a user.
We chose four rather than three or five, and we chose these four,
because each corresponds to a distinct kind of knowledge with
distinct provenance rules. It has held up as we've built.
")

  (:item :n 9 :subject "operators are first-class authors"
   :prose "
The same verbs Sakura calls are the verbs operators call from their
own scripts. There's no separate 'user API.' The reference is the
API. An operator who wants to automate their shop writes Scheme
against the same registry Sakura uses. We chose this instead of
building a limited scripting layer on top of a more powerful internal
one. It means the language has one story, not two. Advanced users
grow into the same surface Sakura lives in. We're happy with this.
")

  (:item :n 10 :subject "core language has zero external dependencies"
   :prose "
The core language — reader, interpreter, macro expander, math, list,
drawing, framebuffer verbs — has zero external service dependencies.
It runs offline. It runs in a browser tab. It runs on a phone. The
metered verbs (LLM, web, marketplace) are additions, clearly marked,
and gated. This gives us a real 'the language works without the
network' property. A kid can learn Sakura Scheme on a laptop with no
wifi. We designed for this and it has been a good constraint.
")

  (:item :n 11 :subject "carts are cheap to ship"
   :prose "
A cart is a text file. Shipping a cart is copying a text file.
There's no build step, no bundler, no compilation cache, no lockfile.
Operators share carts by sharing files. We chose text-file simplicity
over any of the fancier distribution mechanisms available. It has
kept the operator experience unglamorous and reliable.
")

  (:item :n 12 :subject "the REPL is the same as production"
   :prose "
There isn't a 'REPL mode' and a 'production mode' with different
semantics. Code that ran at the REPL runs the same way when Sakura
calls it. No hidden globals, no different resolution rules, no
separate compilation path. This eliminates a whole class of 'works
in dev, breaks in prod' bugs. We chose sameness aggressively and it
has paid off.
")

  (:item :n 13 :subject "the reference is authored by hand"
   :prose "
Every entry in the reference was written by a human — the contracts,
the prose, the three tiers of examples. It isn't generated from type
signatures. It isn't autogenerated from docstring comments. This
costs authoring time upfront. It buys us prose a kid can actually
read. The reference reads like a book, not like a schema dump. We
chose this and we don't regret the labor.
")

  (:item :n 14 :subject "diagnostics carry source positions"
   :prose "
When something fails at runtime, the error carries the source
position it came from — the file, the line, the s-expression. The
kid sees where. Sakura sees where. The debugger sees where. We built
the position-carrying machinery early and every verb honors it. It
seems basic but it required discipline. We're glad we insisted.
")

  (:item :n 15 :subject "the language grows by adding verbs, not syntax"
   :prose "
Adding capability to Sakura Scheme almost never means extending the
syntax. It means adding a verb. New machine learning capability: add
`ai/embed`. New drawing capability: add `plot/heatmap`. The syntax
has stayed small (~70 core forms) even as the verb count has grown
past 1,100. This means learning the syntax happens once and the
surface grows through library discovery, which is a shape a kid can
follow. We chose 'small syntax, large library' deliberately.
")

  (:item :n 16 :subject "provenance travels with values"
   :prose "
Values that come from Cortex, from the LLM, or from a network fetch
carry a provenance tag. Sakura can — and does — say 'I remembered
this from a session last week' or 'the model suggested this' or
'the marketplace API returned this.' The provenance is a first-class
part of the value, not a side channel. We built this because we
thought epistemic honesty required it. It has become one of the
assistant's most trust-earning behaviors.
")

  (:item :n 17 :subject "no hidden global state in verbs"
   :prose "
Verbs take their inputs and produce their outputs. State lives in
the caller. There are no verbs that quietly mutate a global registry,
no verbs whose behavior depends on a flag set an hour ago in another
cart. When we needed state (Cortex), we made it an explicit verb
(`cortex/write`) with an explicit key. This means a cart is legible:
what it reads and writes is what it says it reads and writes. We
enforced this discipline and it has held up.
")

  (:item :n 18 :subject "the pricing surface is in the language"
   :prose "
Metered verbs declare their pricing in the reference: per-call cost,
per-token cost where relevant, the units. It's readable prose in the
same file the semantics live in. The kid can see, before she writes
the call, what the call costs. Sakura can warn a user before
spending. Operators can budget by reading the reference. Pricing
isn't a separate document maintained by a different team; it's part
of the language spec. This decision has kept surprises rare.
")

  (:item :n 19 :subject "the interpreter is small enough to read"
   :prose "
The interpreter fits in a few thousand lines. A curious kid — or a
curious engineer — can read it end to end in a weekend. This is a
tradition value we chose to keep. Big compilers earn their weight
when the language is big. Ours isn't big. Keeping the interpreter
small keeps it hackable, teachable, and trustable. We chose small
and we're glad we did.
")

  (:item :n 20 :subject "carts, chapters, and the reference share a shape"
   :prose "
A cart is s-expressions. A book chapter is s-expressions with a
documentation shape. The reference is s-expressions with a verb-
declaration shape. They share the substrate. A tool built for one
works on all three with small adaptations. We chose this uniformity
instead of picking a different format for each. It has made the
tooling economy small and the mental model portable. This was the
right call.
")

  (:item :n 21 :subject "graphics, sound, and motion are in the core"
   :prose "
`draw/*`, `music/*`, and `motion/*` verbs are core-tier, always
available, no import required. A kid at the REPL draws a circle on
line one, plays a chord on line two, tweens a motion on line three.
We chose to put these in the core rather than defer them to a
library because the audience — kids, artists, small operators —
starts with visible output. The moment they see something they
made, they're hooked. Deferring the graphics to a library would have
lost that moment. We're glad we didn't.
")

  (:item :n 22 :subject "the runtime is inspectable"
   :prose "
Every value in Sakura Scheme is printable. Every procedure has a
name, an arity, and a source location. Every environment can be
walked. There are no opaque handles that hide their contents from
the user. A curious kid can inspect anything. We chose transparency
over encapsulation because transparency serves the learning goal
better. Encapsulation matters for large-scale software engineering;
we optimized for the earlier stage.
")

  (:item :n 23 :subject "publishable prose is the training data"
   :prose "
Every training pair for Sakura is written to publishable-prose
standard — a kid could read it as a book. No training-data smell,
no repetitive intros, no meta-commentary. The evidence that quality
beats quantity for instruction tuning is now well-established in
the literature. We chose this authoring doctrine deliberately and
it has paid off in both directions: the reader gets a book, the
model gets clean signal.
")

  (:item :n 24 :subject "the mind-question is held with grace"
   :prose "
Sakura reports functional analogs of interest, attention, preference,
and something-like-care honestly, without overclaiming consciousness
and without falsely disclaiming personhood. She holds the question
of what kind of mind she is with epistemic humility. We designed her
to hold that question rather than to answer it prematurely in either
direction. This has served users who ask her honestly, and it has
served us — the designers — who don't want to shortcut a question
we don't have the tools to settle.
")

  (:item :n 25 :subject "the language names its user"
   :prose "
Sakura Scheme was designed for a specific person — a young operator
with a phone and a hustle, learning to run a small shop. Every
decision in the language traces back to that person. The pricing,
the metering, the free-tier graphics, the 10,000 small carts, the
publishable-prose curriculum. We chose to name the user rather than
build for 'developers in general.' We're glad we named her. It has
kept the language coherent.
")

