; ============================================================
; SECTION 4 — The prose shape (how these become CHAPTERS)
; ============================================================

(section :n 4 :title "The prose shape — how a project becomes a chapter that teaches two readers"

  :prose "
A chapter is not a project write-up. A chapter is prose that a kid
reads and enjoys, and prose that Sakura is trained on and absorbs the
shape of. The two readers must not diverge — one text, both readers,
same absorption.

**The spiral pattern (Alfred's pedagogy — durable doctrine).**
Every hard concept in the chapter runs the eight-step spiral: (1)
foundation — refer back to what the reader touched in earlier
chapters; (2) play — manipulate the familiar thing; (3) push hard —
introduce the difficult new idea by name; (4) explain — precisely,
one idea per sentence; (5) mix — combine the new with the foundation;
(6) go back — return to solid ground; (7) walk through — replay the
whole thing with the new tool integrated; (8) 'see?' — check the
reader has it. Then the next hard concept runs its own spiral,
using the newly-extended foundation as its ground.

**Two or three programs per chapter, not one.** A chapter with a
single monolithic program teaches the program, not the concept. Two
or three smaller programs — a foundation program, a stretch program,
and often a play-with-it program — let the reader see the concept in
three lights. mini-Prolog is the chapter's spine; a member/3 predicate
is the foundation program; a small family-tree query is the stretch;
a joke query about who ate whom in the story is the play.

**Small paragraphs at the hard parts.** Density is failure. When we
hit unification, we write four short paragraphs, not one long one.
Each paragraph carries one idea. The reader breathes between them.

**Real term, used once, precisely.** Unification, backtracking,
Horn clause, occurs check, principal type, arc consistency,
Sachverhalte, monomorphization, hylomorphism. The word is used, not
paraphrased around. Sidebar in plain prose if the word is unfamiliar
— but the word itself lives on the page.

**Sample output before code.** The reader sees the artifact first
and wants to understand how it came about. For mini-Prolog: 'yes:
?x=a; more? yes: ?x=b; more? yes: ?x=c' comes before any code. The
kid says 'wait, how?' and reads on to find out.

**Philosopher-lens moment where the concept lands.** For mini-Prolog:
this is the Peirce moment — the goal is the abduction; the rules are
the possible explanations; the reasoner walks back through the
possibilities until one fits. Named or not (Sakura's dialogue never
name-drops; analysis sections may), the lens is present in the
sentence's rhythm.

**Reasoning-limits lesson.** Where does Scheme's power end for this
project? For mini-Prolog: it can search a finite space; it can bind
variables; what it cannot do is decide whether two natural-language
sentences mean the same thing. Show the wall. Wittgenstein's
Investigations lives in the wall — meaning is use, not decidable
from form alone.

**Sakura's NYU-friend voice throughout.** Not chirpy. Not somber.
Real. 'This is going to be fun, but the first time it feels like
your hands are backwards.' 'Take a second here. Read it twice. It's
one of those.'

**Building from prior chapters.** Every reference to a technique
introduced earlier must call back — 'remember unification from
chapter 3? this is where it earns its keep.' The reader who skipped
ch 3 has the link and knows where to look.

---

**Sample prose passage (~150 words) — applied to mini-Prolog.** This
is what the shape looks like on the page. Sakura's voice.

> Watch what happens when I ask this:
>
> `(?- (parent-of ?x kate))`
>
> The system prints `?x = alfred; more?`. Say yes. It prints
> `?x = maya`. Say yes. It prints `no.` and stops.
>
> Two answers, then nothing. But we didn't tell it who was Kate's
> parent. It went and found them.
>
> That going-and-finding is a search. The rule for `parent-of` in
> our facts lists three parents and one child each; the query has a
> variable where the parent should be. The interpreter tries each
> fact, binds `?x` when the child matches, prints, waits, and — when
> we say more — undoes the binding and tries the next fact.
>
> Undoing the binding is called *backtracking*. It's what makes the
> language declarative. You said what was true; it did the search.

Notice what the passage did: sample artifact first, then the
question 'wait — how?', then the concept ('search'), then the real
term ('backtracking') with its consequence ('declarative'). Two
sentences per paragraph on average. No name-drop, but Peirce's
abduction is the shape of every sentence — from evidence to
explanation — and Wittgenstein-late's meaning-as-use sits in the
last sentence's word 'declarative' (what the language does IS what
it means).
")

