; ============================================================
; SECTION 6 — Translation strategy
; ============================================================

(section :n 6 :title "Translation strategy — porting canonical algorithms into Sakura Scheme"

  :prose "
Alfred's directive: 'I really want this done in the Scheme, obviously
— or if any is done in any programming language at all and that we
have support for it and can translate.' Every project in Section 3
carries a `:translate-from` field pointing at a canonical source
(SICP, PAIP, Norvig's essays, TAPL, Sutton & Barto, Nielsen NN,
Kernighan & Pike). This section gives the porting rules.

**Direct ports — one-to-one, near-verbatim.** Anything from SICP
lands almost unchanged. `car`, `cdr`, `cons`, `map`, `filter`,
`assoc`, `lambda`, `define`, `let`, `cond`, `if`, `and`, `or` are
identical in Sakura Scheme. Symbolic differentiation from SICP
§2.3.2 is a copy-paste job. The metacircular evaluator from SICP §4.1
is a copy-paste job (with our verb names for the built-ins). PAIP's
Prolog and pattern matcher are near-copy-paste; the biggest edit is
`syntax-rules` → our `defmacro` shape at the top.

**Idiomatic ports — Scheme-to-Scheme with library swaps.** Racket
code ports cleanly but Racket-specific idioms (`match`, `struct`,
`syntax-parse`, `raco`) need replacements. Our `pair?`, `symbol?`,
`equal?` cover most of what `match` gives you for simple cases;
complex matchers get built out (this is Section 3's frequent
`:wire-up-needed (pattern-match)` flag). Racket's `struct` maps to
association lists or our record verbs; `syntax-parse` becomes
`defmacro` with hygiene notes.

**Ported-with-thought — Python, OCaml, Haskell, Common Lisp.** These
languages have shapes Sakura Scheme has to translate rather than copy.
Python's imperative loop `for x in xs: total += x` becomes a
`(reduce + 0 xs)` or an explicit `(let loop ...)`. Python's classes
become association lists or record verbs. OCaml's algebraic data
types become tagged lists (`(node value left right)`). Haskell's
type classes become dispatch on tag by association. The Nielsen
neural-net Python code translates line-for-line if we keep our
`linalg/*` verbs as the matrix layer; Python's NumPy `dot` becomes
`(vec/dot a b)`, `sigmoid` becomes `(define (sigmoid x) (/ 1 (+ 1
(exp (- x)))))`, and the training loop is a tail-recursive `let`.

**Ported-with-full-rewrite — TensorFlow, PyTorch, Django, React.**
Anything that assumes JIT compilation, GPU dispatch, or a large
runtime ecosystem gets rewritten from scratch in the shape that fits
Sakura Scheme. The neural net project (#12) is 'PyTorch's shape,
Sakura Scheme's implementation' — we don't try to reproduce the API,
we teach the underlying algorithm cleanly.

**Verbs that make ports short.**
  - `call/cc` (once wire-up lands) — for CSP/mini-Prolog/backtrack search
  - `sym/derivative`, `sym/expand`, `sym/substitute` — symbolic diff free
  - `linalg/solve`, `linalg/lu`, `linalg/qr`, `vec/+`, `vec/dot` — nn/12
  - `stat/mean`, `stat/sd`, `stat/histogram` — Bayes/bandit
  - `cortex/read`, `cortex/write`, `cortex/topk` — mini-RAG (needs SLAT entry)
  - `ai/policy`, `ai/decide`, `ai/utility` — bandit / RL / actor / IF-cast
  - `game/frame`, `game/step`, `game/state` — roguelike, chess loop
  - `ai/grid`, `ai/wall!`, `ai/path`, `ai/passable?` — roguelike terrain
  - `plot/graph`, `plot/histogram` — every project with output
  - `audit-verify` — event-source ledger, invariant-checking

**Verbs still to wire (called out in Section 3 projects).**
Common wire-up gaps flagged across the 25 projects:
  - `unify`, `occurs-check`, `substitute`, `pattern-match` (used across
    logic projects #1, #2, #3, #6, #7)
  - `llm/complete`, `llm/embed`, `llm/classify` (mini-RAG #8, poetry #18)
  - `tokenize` (#9, #10)
  - `syllable-count`, `rhyme-of` (#18)
  - `chess/legal-moves`, `chess/evaluate` (#21)
  - `nn/init`, `nn/step` (#12)
  - `parse`, `codegen`, `spawn`, `send`, `receive` (#14, #16)
  - `unit-convert`, `ingredient-swap` (#20)
  - `interval-overlap` (#25)
  - `cortex/read`, `cortex/write`, `cortex/topk` — implemented in
    `wired-verbs.js` but MISSING from SLAT reference; needs SLAT entry
    so the reference-loader teaches these to the reader and to Sakura.

**When to write from scratch vs port.** Port when a canonical source
exists and its shape is what we want the reader to learn. Write from
scratch when (a) the shape we want is different from any published
source (e.g., Interactive-fiction-with-Flower-Stories-cast, project
#23), (b) the canonical source uses machinery we don't have (e.g., a
dependent-type version of Hindley-Milner is out of scope; the vanilla
Algorithm W is the port target), or (c) the pedagogy of the port
would drag in irrelevant complexity (e.g., Nielsen's book scales up
to CNNs; we stop at one hidden layer because that's what teaches
backprop cleanly).

**Rule of thumb.** If you can find the algorithm in SICP, PAIP,
Norvig's essays, Nielsen's NN book, Kernighan & Pike, Sutton & Barto,
Harrison's Logic book, or the TAPL text — port it. If not, write it,
carefully, with a real prior citation for the concept even if not
the code.
")

